<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910814-0104</DOCNO><DOCID>910814-0104.</DOCID><HL>   No Charges   Are Expected   In Pandamp;G Affair   ----   By James S. Hirsch   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>08/14/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3</SO><CO>   DJ PG</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS AND SERVICES (HOU)CONSUMER AND HOUSEHOLD PRODUCTS (HPR)LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><NS>LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES, HEARINGS, RULINGS, LEGISLATION (LAW)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)OHIO (OH)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   The active phase of the investigation into the source ofnews leaks to The Wall Street Journal about Procter andamp; GambleCo. appears to be coming to an end, and no criminal chargesare expected.   &quot;It's winding down,&quot; said Gary Armstrong, specialinvestigator for the Cincinnati police department's fraudsquad unit.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Armstrong declined to comment on the results of themonthlong investigation, and Terry Gaines, first assistantprosecutor in Hamilton County, said he was unfamiliar withthe progress of the police investigation. But a Pandamp;G spokesmansaid it appears unlikely that criminal charges will be filedagainst any individuals.   Paul E. Steiger, managing editor of The Wall StreetJournal, said, &quot;We're pleased that it's winding down butwe're concerned that it ever began in the first place becauseof its obvious chilling effect on the news-gatheringprocess.&quot;   The Cincinnati fraud squad initiated the investigationafter Pandamp;G complained that confidential and proprietaryinformation had been leaked to the Journal, which ispublished by Dow Jones andamp; Co. At least one former Pandamp;G managerwas brought in for questioning, but Mr. Armstrong declined tosay how many people he interviewed.   As part of the inquiry, the police used a grand-jurysubpoena to obtain Cincinnati Bell Inc. records of telephoneconversations between area residents and the Journal'sPittsburgh bureau, which covers Pandamp;G. They have also examinedrecords of calls made to the Pittsburgh residence of Journalreporter Alecia Swasy.   Responding to critical press coverage of Pandamp;G's actions, aspokesman reaffirmed the company's support of First Amendmentrights. The press &quot;has the right to pursue information, butwe have the right to protect proprietary information,&quot; hesaid. In taking its case to the police, the consumer productsconcern said there were possible violations of an Ohio lawthat prohibits employees from disclosing company secrets.</TEXT></DOC>